revision.text:
'''Antipater''' ({{lang-grc|Ἀντίπατρος}}) of [[Acanthus (Greece)|Acanthus]] was a [[Grammarian (Greco-Roman world)|grammarian]] of [[ancient Greece]], of uncertain date,<ref>[[Ptolemaeus Chennus]], ''ap. [[Bibliotheca (Photius)|Phot. Cod.]]''</ref><ref>[[Eustathius of Thessalonica]], ''ad [[Homer|Hom.]] [[Odyssey|Od.]]'' xi. p. 453</ref> probably the same as the one mentioned by the [[Scholiast]] on [[Aristophanes]].<ref>Scholiast on [[Aristophanes]] Av. 1403</ref>

Some scholars consider this Antipater to be entirely fictional, and a source fabricated by [[Ptolemaeus Chennus]], to assert the existence of a version of the [[Iliad]] that predates [[Homer]]'s, written, Ptolemaeus said, by [[Dares Phrygius]], a participant in the events of the [[Trojan War]].<ref>{{cite book | last =Mheallaigh | first =Karen ní | title =Reading Fiction with Lucian: Fakes, Freaks and Hyperreality | publisher =[[Cambridge University Press]] | series =Greek Culture in the Roman World | date =2014 | pages =122 | url =https://books.google.ie/books?id=cru1BAAAQBAJ | isbn = 9781316123980 | accessdate=2016-01-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last =Allen | first =Thomas William | title =The Homeric Catalogue of Ships | publisher =Georg Olms Verlag | date =1921 | pages =30 | url =https://books.google.ie/books?id=uf0qfxC5LjIC | isbn = 9783487420592 | accessdate=2016-01-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last =Kim | first =Lawrence | title =Homer between History and Fiction in Imperial Greek Literature | publisher =[[Cambridge University Press]] | series =Greek Culture in the Roman World | date =2010 | pages =179 | url =https://books.google.ie/books?id=K7Bg3zRom6QC | isbn = 9781139490245 | accessdate=2016-01-30}}</ref>

