[[File:Cantius-Stele 20130724.jpg|thumb|The Cantius-Stele in the Lapidarium of the Archäologiemuseums Schloss Eggenberg]]
The '''Cantius Stele''' is a Roman grave stele in the form of a rectangular [[aedicula]] from [[Noricum]], which was created around AD 100.

The stele, which measures 288 x 116 x 29 cm is made of [[Gummern marble]] and divides into four horizontal sections. The uppermost, the [[Tympanum (architecture)|tympanum]] is composed of a triangular gable with a [[gorgoneion]] in the centre and two dolphins facing outwards in the spandrels. Underneath this are laurel wreathed medallions containing portraits of Lucius Cantius Secundus and his wife Cantia Bonia, between two twisting columns. Below this, in a similar but centred medallion is an image of their daughter Cantia Boniata, with an image of a boy to the left and of a girl to the right. The lowest section is the inscription, which reads:

{{quote|text=
{{columns|width=auto
|col1={{lang-la|L(ucius) Cantius / Secundus v(ivus) f(ecit) sib(i) / et Cantiae Iuni(i) f(iliae) / Boniae uxori et / Cantiae L(ucii) f(iliae) Boniatae}}
|col2={{lang-en|Lucius Cantius Secundus made this while still alive for himself and his wife Cantia Bonia daughter of Iunius and for his daughter Cantia Boniata}}
}}|sign={{CIL|3|5437}} & {{CIL|3|5438}}}}
The stele was embedded in the outer wall of [[St Leonhard's, Graz|St Leonhard's]] in [[Graz]] until 1818, when it was gifted to the collection of the [[Universalmuseum Joanneum|Landesmuseum Joanneum]]. Today it is kept in the [[lapidarium]] of the archaeological museum at [[Eggenberg Palace, Graz|Eggenberg Palace]]

