[[File:Jaan Eilart 83.jpg|thumb|Jaan Eilart in 1983]] '''Jaan Eilart''' (24 June 1933 – 18 May 2006) was an [[Estonia]]n [[Phytogeography|phytogeographer]], [[Landscape ecology|landscape ecologist]], [[Cultural history|cultural historian]] and [[Conservation (ethic)|conservationist]].
Eilart was born in [[Pala, Järva County|Pala]], Kirna Parish, [[Järva County]]. In 1957 he started teaching [[Conservation (ethic)|conservation]] as a subject in the [[University of Tartu|Tartu State University]]. In 1958 he established the [[Tartu Students' Nature Protection Circle]] ({{lang-et|Tartu Üliõpilaste Looduskaitsering}}; TÜLKR), which is allegedly the oldest student's community dedicated to conservation, and in 1966 he established the [[Estonian Nature Conservation Society]] ({{lang|et|Eesti Looduskaitse Selts}}; ELKS). In 1969 Eilart led the establishment of [[Lahemaa National Park]] which was the first [[national park]] in the [[Soviet Union]]. Later he also instructed the establishment of national parks in [[Komi Republic|Komi]], [[Armenia]] and [[Tajikistan]]. Eilart held the chair of Eastern-European Committee of [[International Union for Conservation of Nature|IUCN]] from 1982 to 1990.<ref name=elks>{{cite web|title=Jaan Eilart|url=http://www.elks.ee/index.php?id=417|publisher=[[Estonian Nature Conservation Society|ELKS]]|accessdate=29 November 2012}}</ref> He died, aged 72, in [[Tartu]].
